00:09:17.950 --> 00:09:23.690
Okay, Part 7, Ashoka. Remember that for most
of Indian history, India it was not one unified

00:09:23.690 --> 00:09:28.240
place. It was tons of different principalities
and city-states and everything else. But India

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:32.260
did experience indigenous political unity
twice, first under the Mauryan Dynasty in

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:36.220
the 3rd century BCE. And then again under
the Gupta Dynasty from the 300’s to the

00:09:36.220 --> 00:09:38.560
500’s CE, but we’re not going to talk
about that because it bores me.

00:09:38.560 --> 00:09:42.940
Right now, we’re interested in one particular
leader from the Mauryan Dynasty, Ashoka, because

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:47.380
Ashoka attempted to rule through quasi-Buddhist
principles. So Ashoka was initially a warrior

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:51.890
who ended up expanding the empire that his
grandfather started. And Ashoka experienced

00:09:51.890 --> 00:09:57.300
this conversion to Buddhism after he saw his
own army devastate the Kingdom of Kalinga,

00:09:57.300 --> 00:10:00.190
something I bring up primarily so that I can
say Kingdom of Kalinga.

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:04.530
Stan, is there anyway we can write a song
a song about that, like, Kingdom of Kalinga/

00:10:04.530 --> 00:10:07.670
I’m sorry you got destroyed...

00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:10.800
So, Ashoka built stupas, (stoopas?) Hold on...

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:12.180
HowJSay: Stoopah.

00:10:12.180 --> 00:10:15.640
John: Could he have said that any more pretentiously?
Stupas.

00:10:15.640 --> 00:10:20.040
So Ashoka built stupas, these mound-like monuments
to the Buddha, all over his kingdom to show

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:24.230
his devotion. And he also put up pillars throughout
his empire that proclaimed his benevolent

00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:27.470
rule and said he was going to rule through
something he called dhamma, which according

00:10:27.470 --> 00:10:32.300
to one of the pillars went like this: "proper
behavior towards servants and employees, respect

00:10:32.300 --> 00:10:38.050
for mother and father, generosity to friends,
companions, relations, Brahmans and ascetics,

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:39.740
and not killing living beings."

00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:43.470
So those are not individualistic goals like
we see in Hinduism; they’re relational goals,

00:10:43.470 --> 00:10:47.090
like we’re gonna see next week when we study
Confucianism. And that’s one of the reasons

00:10:47.090 --> 00:10:51.490
why Ashoka’s empire wasn’t actually very
Buddhist because ultimately Buddhism isn’t

00:10:51.490 --> 00:10:55.450
that concerned with the order of the world.
Buddhism argues that the fulfillment of the

00:10:55.450 --> 00:10:59.330
self will lead to the order of the world.
In the end, Ashoka’s empire didn’t outlast

00:10:59.330 --> 00:11:03.860
him by much, and soon enough Buddhism declined
in India, almost to the point of extinction.

00:11:03.860 --> 00:11:07.990
Part 8: The Big Finish. So as anyone who has
ever practices yoga knows, Hinduism is the

00:11:07.990 --> 00:11:12.050
most flexible of all the world religions,
which is part of the reason it’s often described

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:15.350
as polytheistic. The belief that god(s) can
take many different forms makes it easy for

00:11:15.350 --> 00:11:20.470
Hinduism to assimilate other religious traditions.
Which is exactly what happened with Buddhism.

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:24.080
In time the Buddha came to be worshipped as
another incarnation of one of the Hindu gods,

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:28.920
and not as a mortal teacher. So in the end, Hinduism,
rather than purging the Buddha, enveloped him.

00:11:28.930 --> 00:11:32.930
So all this means that while Hinduism has
a tremendous amount of variety and flexibility,

00:11:32.930 --> 00:11:38.520
its core tenets of samsara, karma, and the
caste system have provided a remarkable amount

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:42.260
of cultural and social unity to the Indian
subcontinent for millennia.

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:45.520
Fortunately for the Buddha, his teachings
migrated East to China. We’re gonna make

